# Date.now() - JavaScript | MDNMDN Web DocsMDN logoMozilla logo

The **`Date.now()`** static method returns the number of milliseconds elapsed since the [epoch](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date#the_epoch_timestamps_and_invalid_date), which is defined as the midnight at the beginning of January 1, 1970, UTC.

## [Try it](#try_it)

## [Syntax](#syntax)

### [Parameters](#parameters)

None.

### [Return value](#return_value)

A number representing the [timestamp](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date#the_epoch_timestamps_and_invalid_date), in milliseconds, of the current time.

## [Description](#description)

### [Reduced time precision](#reduced_time_precision)

To offer protection against timing attacks and [fingerprinting](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/Fingerprinting), the precision of `Date.now()` might get rounded depending on browser settings. In Firefox, the `privacy.reduceTimerPrecision` preference is enabled by default and defaults to 2ms. You can also enable `privacy.resistFingerprinting`, in which case the precision will be 100ms or the value of `privacy.resistFingerprinting.reduceTimerPrecision.microseconds`, whichever is larger.

For example, with reduced time precision, the result of `Date.now()` will always be a multiple of 2, or a multiple of 100 (or `privacy.resistFingerprinting.reduceTimerPrecision.microseconds`) with `privacy.resistFingerprinting` enabled.

```
// reduced time precision (2ms) in Firefox 60
Date.now();
// Might be:
// 1519211809934
// 1519211810362
// 1519211811670
// …

// reduced time precision with `privacy.resistFingerprinting` enabled
Date.now();
// Might be:
// 1519129853500
// 1519129858900
// 1519129864400
// …
```

## [Examples](#examples)

### [Measuring time elapsed](#measuring_time_elapsed)

You can use `Date.now()` to get the current time in milliseconds, then subtract a previous time to find out how much time elapsed between the two calls.

```
const start = Date.now();
doSomeLongRunningProcess();
console.log(`Time elapsed: ${Date.now() - start} ms`);
```

For more complex scenarios, you may want to use the [performance API](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Performance_API/High_precision_timing) instead.

